data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already didn't support true synchronous I/O — it ran sync-over-async internally and you opted in to suppress the warning/error. **In EF Core 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** Every synchronous LINQ operator and `SaveChanges()` call against the Cosmos provider will throw an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

**Affected calls in your code:**
| Sync (breaks) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(…)` | `FirstAsync(…)` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Migrated version

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `async Task<T>` return types replace synchronous returns, and callers must be updated to `await`.
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in-memory; no I/O occurs until `SaveChangesAsync()`.
- There is **no workaround** in .NET 11 to re-enable sync-over-async on the Cosmos provider. The migration to async is mandatory.
